07164nam a22007335i 9780773568693DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735686937 a10.1515/97807735686932doi  a(DE-B1597)654842  a(OCoLC)1394872104  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE3542.Z85bB487 2001eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a346.71/0641 aPhillips, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween State and Market :bEssay on Charities Law and Policy in Canada /cJim Phillips, David Stevens, Bruce Chapman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (712 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tThe Canadian Charitable Sector: An Overview -- tEmpirical and Ethical Perspectives -- tAltruism in Comparative International Perspective -- tAltruism in Philosophical and Ethical Traditions: Two Views -- tRational Voluntarism and the Charitable Sector -- tThe Role of the Voluntary Sector in a Modern Welfare State -- tThe Legal Meaning of Charity -- tThe Federal Court of Appeal and the Legal Meaning of Charity: Review and Critique -- tRethinking Public Benefit: The Definition of Charity in the Era of the Charter -- tThe Doctrine of Political Purposes in the Law of Charities: A Conceptual Analysis -- tReligion, Charity, and the Charter of Rights -- tCharity and the Income Tax Act: The Supreme Court Speaks -- tCharity and Tax: Policy and Practice -- tRegulating Virtue: A Purposive Approach to the Administration of Charities -- tCharitable Contributions and the Personal Income Tax: Evaluating the Canadian Credit -- tThe Tax Credit for Charitable Contributions: Giving Credit where None Is Due -- tRegulatory Challenges -- tThe Regulation of Social Enterprise -- tFlirting with the Devil while Doing God’s Work: The Regulation of Charitable Fund-raising -- tFraming an Appropriate Corporate Law0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first section of the book contains an overview of the charitable sector in Canada, a sociological review of altruism in different societies, a discussion of altruism in various philosophical and religious traditions, an economic analysis of "rational voluntarism," and an assessment of the relationship between the charitable sector and the welfare state. The second section contains five papers on the legal definition of charity, both general (the jurisprudence of the Federal Court of Appeal and a proposal for rethinking the concept of "public benefit"), and particular (the political purposes doctrine, religion as charity, and a commentary on the recent major Supreme Court decision on the meaning of charity). The third section deals with the tax status of charities: two papers evaluate the current tax credit system and one deals with the administration of charities by the Canada Customs and Revenue Agency. The final section contains essays on charities and commercial enterprise, on the regulation of fund-raising, and on needed reforms in non-profit corporation law. At a time when the federal government is about to embark on a wide range of policy initiatives to assist and regulate the non-profit sector, these essays are necessary reading for anyone concerned with the future of the charitable sector in Canada. Contributors include Neil Brooks (Osgoode Hall Law School), Cara Cameron (McGill), Bruce Chapman, Kevin Davis (Toronto), Abraham Drassinower (Toronto), David Duff (Toronto), Richard Janda (McGill), Will Kymlicka (Queen's), Andrée Lajoie (Montreal), Mayo Moran (Toronto), Charles-Maxime Panaccio (office of Mr Justice Charles Gonthier), Jim Phillips, Jane Allyn Piliavin (Wisconsin-Madison), David Sharpe (Attorney-General's Office, New York State), Lorne Sossin (Osgoode Hall Law School), David Stevens, and Jen-Chieh Ting (Academia Sinica).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBrooks, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Cara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChapman, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Kevin E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrassinower, Abraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuff, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanda, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLajoie, Andrée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Mayo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanaccio, Charles-Maxime, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiliavin, Jane Allyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharpe, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSossin, Lorne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStevens, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTing, Jen-Chieh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-